Direct Edit Information
Finish directly editing the mesh body and return to parametric modeling in the Design workspace.
Direct Mesh Editing
Automatically generates face groups on a mesh body using the normal angles between faces to determine the boundaries of each face group.

To display face groups, expand Display Settings > Mesh Display, then check Face Groups. Select mesh bodies or face groups, select the generation method, then adjust the face opening angle, tolerance, and minimal area ratio.
To display face groups, expand Display Settings > Mesh Display, then check Face Groups.

When you insert a mesh that has no face groups, use the Fast generation method to generate an initial set of face groups on the mesh body. Then select specific sets of face groups and use the Accurate generation method to capture detailed areas more accurately.
Generate Face Groups Information
Joins, intersects, cuts, or merges two or more mesh bodies to create a single mesh body.
Select the target body, select one or more tool bodies to combine with the target body, then select the operation to use to combine the bodies together.
You can also choose to create a new component to contain the combined bodies or keep a copy of the original bodies.
Overlapping boundary edges are stitched.
Combine Information
Converts a mesh body to a solid or surface body.

Select the mesh body to convert, then select the operation and method. In the browser and the canvas, the mesh body converts to a solid or surface body. Face groups are used to infer prismatic features.
If the mesh body is watertight, it coverts to a solid body. If the mesh is not watertight, it converts to a surface body.

Use the Faceted operation to generate one face on the solid or surface body for each individual face on the mesh body.Use the Prismatic operationto convert geometry originally created using solid or surface modeling tools.Use the Organic operation to convert geometry originally created from scan data or organic modeling tools.
Convert Mesh Information
Creates a face group from a selection of faces on a mesh body.

To display face groups, expand Display Settings > Mesh Display, then check Face Groups. Select faces on a mesh body to include in the face group. Adjust the settings in the Mesh Selection Palette to refine the selection set.
You can select any faces on the same mesh body to include in the face group, even if they are not connected.
Create Face Group Information
Converts a parametric mesh body to a mesh body.
Creates an empty Mesh Base Feature.
Removes and replaces faces on a mesh body to fill holes and repair regions.
Select the boundary of faces around a hole to fill, or select the faces of a region to remove and replace.

Use the Uniform type to achieve the smoothest and most usable result. Use the Minimal type to reduce the number of triangles on the mesh body, but note the long, thin triangular faces may be more difficult to work with downstream.
Hover over a face along the boundary of a hole in the mesh body, then double-click to select all the faces along the edge of the boundary and fill the hole.
Erase And Fill Information
Separates regions of a mesh body into independent mesh bodies.
Select a separation type, then select a mesh body or face groups to separate into individual bodies.
You can keep a copy of the original mesh body or choose to replace it.
After you generate face groups on a mesh body, use Separate to split features or regions into independent mesh bodies to make it easier to work with them.
Separate Information
To display face groups, expand Display Settings > Mesh Display, then check Face Groups.
Hollows the interior of a mesh body.
Select a mesh body, then adjust the direction and thickness to hollow the interior volume.
You can use the Shell command to hollow a mesh body and significantly reduce the amount of print material, time, and cost required for 3D printing.
Shell Information
Inserts an existing STL, OBJ, or 3MF file as a mesh body into the active component in a design.
Select a file to insert. The contents of the file displays as a mesh body in the canvas and the browser.
For STL or OBJ files, select the unit type that matches the units from the original design that generated the STL or OBJ.

If you insert an OBJ or 3MF file with existing textures, they will display on the mesh body in the canvas. Turn off the Mesh Display > Face Groups display setting to see the textures on the mesh body.
Insert Mesh Information
Combines two or more adjacent face groups on a mesh body.
To display face groups, expand Display Settings > Mesh Display, then check Face Groups. Select two or more adjacent face groups on the mesh body to combine them.
To display face groups, expand Display Settings > Mesh Display, then check Face Groups.
You can combine two or more face groups on a mesh body as long as they share a common edge.
Combine Face Groups Information
Creates a sketch that contains a section line where a plane intersects a mesh body.
Select a mesh body, select a plane, then adjust the location of the section line. Edit the sketch and use the Fit Curves To Mesh Section command to create sketch geometry to match the section line.

Create a series of mesh section sketches to reverse-engineer complex mesh bodies. Edit each section sketch and use the Fit Curves To Mesh Section command to generate a series of sketch profiles. You can use the sketch profiles to create parametric solid and surface bodies to recreate the design.
Create Mesh Section Sketch Information
Uses a plane to trim or split a mesh body.

Select a mesh body, then select and position the cutting plane. The cut can trim the body, split the body into multiple bodies, or split the faces only. For the Trim and Split Body cut types, select a fill type to generate watertight bodies.
Adjust the Fill Type to either leave a mesh open or close the mesh body after you cut it. You can fill the voids that the cut plane leaves behind with either uniform or minimal mesh faces.

Use the Plane Cut command to slice a mesh body along a plane and either trim away one side of the body, split the mesh body into two separate bodies, or slice the mesh faces but leave the mesh body whole.
Plane Cut Information
Reduces the number of faces on a mesh body to minimize complexity.
Select a mesh body or face groups, select a reduction target, then adjust the settings to reduce the number of mesh faces.
Use the Adaptive remesh type to preserve details. Use the Uniform remesh type to keep face sizes relatively even.

Use the Tolerance reduction type to reduce complexity and improve computational performance while working with the mesh. The Tolerance reduction type merges faces while remaining within a maximum deviation from the original mesh shape.
Reduce Information
Refines or coarsens faces on a mesh body or face groups.
Select a mesh body or face groups on a mesh body, then adjust the settings to regenerate the mesh faces.
Use the Adaptive remesh type to preserve details. Use the Uniform remesh type tokeep face sizes relatively even.
Remesh Information
Remove meshes

Select the mesh bodies to be removed. For every mesh which is removed, a feature appears in the timeline. The removal can be, in contrast to delete, be undone and meshes can be restored parametrically.
Repairs a mesh body to prepare it for further design and manufacturing operations.
Select a mesh body to repair, then select a repair type. For the Rebuild repair type, select a rebuild type, then adjust density and offset.

Use the Repair command to fix errors in a mesh body to prepare it for further design and manufacturing operations. Errors may include holes in the mesh body or suboptimal arrangement, orientation, or intersection of triangles in the mesh body.

Use the Close Holes or Stitch and Remove repair types for faster results and fewer changes to the mesh body. For more complex repairs, use the Wrap or Rebuild repair types, but keep in mind that these will take longer to compute and will make more significant changes to the mesh body.
Repair Information
Reverses the normal direction of selected faces on a mesh body.
Select faces on a mesh body to reverse their normal direction.
Some faces on imported mesh bodies may be oriented incorrectly, and the Reverse Normal command lets you orient those faces correctly in a targeted way.
Reverse Normal Information
Scales mesh bodies from a reference point.
Select mesh bodies, select a reference point to scale from and a scale type, then specify the scale factor to scale the mesh bodies.
Select multiple mesh bodies to scale them all at once from a common reference point.
Use the Nonuniform scale type to scale mesh bodies by a different scale factor along the X, Y, and Z axes.
Scale Mesh Information
Smooths rough or creased regions on a mesh body.
Select a mesh body or face groups, select a smoothing type, then adjust the smoothness and scale to smooth rough or creased regions.
Use the Smooth command to soften rough areas or sharp creases on a mesh body.
Specify Smoothness on a scale from 0-1.00, where 0 applies minimal smoothing effects to the mesh body and 1.00 applies maximum smoothing effects.
Smooth Information
Converts an existing solid or surface body into a mesh body.
Select the solid or surface body to tessellate, then adjust the mesh refinement settings to convert the body to a mesh body.
Start with one of the Refinement presets, then customize the refinement settings to fine-tune the result before you complete the tessellation.
Check the Preview setting to see what the new mesh body will look like as you adjust the Refinement Settings.
Tesselate Information
Converts a mesh body or face groups with triangular faces to a mesh body or face groups with quad faces.
Select a mesh body or face groups, select an output type, then adjust the settings to convert from triangular to quad faces.
